[src:matthew-hay/30-31-vict-p03] This act was not printed by the Queen's Printer.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] The council has been under no overall control since 2002.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] Since 2022 it has been led by a Scottish National Party and Liberal Democrat coalition.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] It meets at Aberdeen Town House and has its main offices at the neighbouring Marischal College.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] Aberdeen was made a royal burgh by David I (reigned 1124–1153).
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] The burgh of Aberdeen was governed by a corporation, also known as the town council.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] Elections for the council were only introduced in 1833.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] Prior to that the council was not an elected body; when vacancies arose the existing council appointed successors.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] As Aberdeen grew, the council's powers were inadequate to cater for the needs of the growing urban area.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] A separate police commission was established in 1795 with powers to levy taxes and provide infrastructure ('police' in this context being its older meaning of civic government rather than law enforcement).
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] The first police commission was short-lived, but it was resurrected in 1818 after the town council went bankrupt in 1817.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] From 1818 until 1871 there was a dual system of local government, with the town council and police commission having different roles in Aberdeen's administration.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] The police commission was eventually abolished in 1871 and its functions absorbed by the town council.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] Aberdeen was historically part of Aberdeenshire, but the functions affecting the burgh which operated at county level were relatively few, largely being limited to judicial functions and lieutenancy.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] When elected county councils were created in 1890 under the Local Government (Scotland) Act 1889, Aberdeen Corporation was deemed capable of running county-level local government functions, and so the burgh was excluded from the area administered by Aberdeenshire County Council.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] In 1891 Aberdeen's boundaries were significantly enlarged, absorbing the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside, plus the Torry area on the south bank of the River Dee.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] The act of parliament which expanded the burgh also confirmed that Aberdeen was entitled to be called a city; it had commonly been described as a city prior to that, but (like most Scottish cities) without official recognition.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] The historic county boundary between Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire in this area followed the River Dee.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] Following the absorption of Torry on the south bank of the river in 1891, the city straddled the two counties.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] Aberdeen was made a county of itself in 1899, removing the city from the two counties for lieutenancy and other purposes as well as local government functions.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] The city boundaries were subsequently enlarged several times, gaining further territory from both Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire, notably in 1935, 1952 and 1970.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] Local government across Scotland was reorganised in 1975 under the Local Government (Scotland) Act 1973, which replaced the counties, burghs and landward districts with a two-tier system of regions and districts.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] One of the districts was called 'City of Aberdeen', which formed part of Grampian Region.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] City of Aberdeen District Council was therefore a lower-tier district authority, with upper-tier regional functions being provided by Grampian Regional Council.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] The City of Aberdeen district covered a larger area than the pre-1975 city, taking in the parishes of Dyce, Newhills, Old Machar, and Peterculter from Aberdeenshire and Nigg from Kincardineshire.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] All except Dyce had previously ceded territory to the city in pre-1975 boundary changes.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] The parish of Nigg added in 1975 just covered the residual rural parts of the old parish around Cove Bay; Nigg village itself had been absorbed into the city in 1935.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] The parish of Old Machar was named after St Machar's Cathedral in Old Aberdeen, which had been absorbed into the city in 1891; the parish of Old Machar that was absorbed in 1975 was just the residual part of the cathedral's old parish which lay north of the River Don, including Bridge of Don.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] Local government was reorganised again in 1996 under the Local Government etc.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] (Scotland) Act 1994, which abolished the regions and districts created in 1975 and established 32 single-tier council areas across Scotland.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] The existing City of Aberdeen District became one of the new council areas.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] The 1994 Act named the new council area 'City of Aberdeen', but this was changed to 'Aberdeen City' by a council resolution on 9 May 1995, before the new council area came into force, allowing the new council to take the name 'Aberdeen City Council'.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] Following the 2022 election a Scottish National Party and Liberal Democrats coalition took control of the council.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] The first election to the City of Aberdeen District Council was held in 1974, initially operating as a shadow authority alongside the outgoing authorities until the new system came into force on 16 May 1975.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] A shadow authority was again elected in 1995 ahead of the change to council areas which came into force on 1 April 1996.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] The role of Lord Provost of Aberdeen is largely ceremonial.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] They chair full council meetings and act as the council's civic figurehead.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] Political leadership is provided by the leader of the council.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] Aberdeen City Council currently comprises 45 councillors, who represent the city's wards, and is headed by the Lord Provost.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] Prior to the 2012 council election there were 43 members of Aberdeen City Council.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] Between 2003 and 2007, the council was under the control of a Liberal Democrat and Conservative coalition, holding 23 of the 43 seats on the council.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] Prior to the 2003 election, the council had been considered a Labour stronghold.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] Two Liberal Democrat councillors became independents during this period due to personal controversies, while the four strong Conservative group split in August 2010, with two councillors forming the Scottish Conservative Group and two others the Aberdeen Conservative Group.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] After the May 2012 election, the control of the council shifted back to the Labour Party, supported in a coalition by three Conservative and three Independent councillors, giving the administration 23 seats.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] The Labour/Conservative/Independent coalition continued after the 2017 election, but with a change in the balance of power within the coalition.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] Labour were reduced to nine councillors (subsequently suspended from membership by the Scottish Labour Party for forming a coalition with the Conservatives), whilst the Conservatives had eleven councillors elected.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] These Conservative and suspended "Aberdeen Labour" councillors were joined in coalition by three Independent councillors, one of who had left the Liberal Democrats just days after the council election.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] In December 2019 a councillor elected as a Conservative became an Independent following his conviction for sexual assault.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] This led to the ruling coalition becoming a minority administration comprising only 22 of the 45 councillors.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] Between 2017 and 2021 the council had Co-Leaders Douglas Lumsden (Conservative) and Jenny Laing (“Aberdeen Labour”) as a result of the coalition agreement.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] Following Douglas Lumsden's election to the Scottish Parliament in May 2021 Jenny Laing became sole Leader of the council.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] After the 2022 election the SNP and Liberal Democrats agreed to form a partnership to lead the Council for the next five years.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] At the Council's statutory meeting on 18 May 2022, SNP councillor David Cameron was elected Lord Provost and Liberal Democrat Councillor Steve Delaney was elected Depute Provost.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] SNP Group Leader Alex Nicoll and Liberal Democrat Group Leader Ian Yuill became Co-Leaders of the Council.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] Effective April 2, 2026, Desmond Buchanan, Councillor for George Street/Harbour ward resigned.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] The Returning Officer announced the By-Election will take place on Thursday, June 25th 2026.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] Council meetings are held at Aberdeen Town House on Broad Street, which was built in 1874 and substantially extended in 1975, including a new council chamber.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] The council's main offices are now in the neighbouring Marischal College.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] The council moved into the renovated former college building in 2011.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] Before May 2007, councillors represented 43 single-member wards election on a first-past-the-post basis.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] On 3 May 2007, the single transferable vote system was used for the first time and multi-member wards were introduced, each ward electing three or four councillors.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] The Local Government Boundary Commission for Scotland completed its final recommendations for new wards for all the council areas of Scotland.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] Aberdeen is divided into 13 multi-member wards, electing a total of 45 councillors.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-city-council] This system was introduced as a result of the Local Governance (Scotland) Act 2004, and is designed to produce a form of proportional representation.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen received royal burgh status from David I of Scotland (1124–1153), which transformed the city economically.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The traditional industries of fishing, paper-making, shipbuilding, and textiles have been overtaken by the oil industry and Aberdeen's seaport.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Heliport is one of the busiest commercial heliports in the world, and the seaport is the largest in the north-east part of Scotland.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] A university town, the city is known for the University of Aberdeen, founded in 1495 as King's College, the fifth oldest university in the English-speaking world and located in Old Aberdeen.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] During the mid-18th to mid-20th centuries, Aberdeen's buildings incorporated locally quarried grey granite, which may sparkle like silver because of its high mica content.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Since the discovery of North Sea oil in 1969, Aberdeen has been known as the offshore **oil capital of Europe**.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Based upon the discovery of prehistoric villages around the mouths of the rivers Dee and Don, the area around Aberdeen is thought to have been settled for at least 6,000 years.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The name given to Aberdeen translates as 'mouth of the river Don', and is recorded as Aberdon in 1172 and Aberden in c.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The first element of the name is the Pictish word *aber* 'river mouth'.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The second element is from the Celtic river goddess Devona.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is usually described as within the historical Pictish territory and became Gaelic-speaking at some time in the medieval period.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Old Aberdeen is the approximate location of Aberdon, the first settlement of Aberdeen; this literally means "the mouth of the Don".
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The Celtic word *aber* means "river mouth", as in modern Welsh (Aberystwyth, Aberdare, Aberbeeg etc.).
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The Scottish Gaelic name is *Obar Dheathain* (variation: *Obairreadhain*; **obar* presumably being a loan from the earlier Pictish; the Gaelic term is *inbhir*), and in Latin, the Romans referred to the river as *Devana*.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Medieval (or Ecclesiastical) Latin has it as *Aberdonia*.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The local Doric pronunciation, [ˌeːbərˈdin] ⓘ or [ˈeːbərdin] ⓘ (with a long *ay* sound), is frequently rendered *Aiberdeen* or *Aiberdein*.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen area has seen human settlement for at least 8,000 years.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The city began as two separate burghs: Old Aberdeen at the mouth of the river Don; and New Aberdeen, a fishing and trading settlement, where the Denburn waterway entered the river Dee estuary.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The earliest charter was granted by William the Lion in 1179 and confirmed the corporate rights granted by David I.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] In 1214, Aberdeen Burgesses were granted a Royal Charter by Alexander II of Scotland giving them the sole right to form a Guild.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] This body exercised power in the composition of the local council, and the affairs of the town.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The Burgesses of the Guild were an integral part of the council for more than 700 years and played a considerable role in the growth and development of Aberdeen.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] In 1319, the Great Charter of Robert the Bruce transformed Aberdeen into a property-owning and financially independent community.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Granted with it was the nearby Forest of Stocket, whose income formed the basis for the city's Common Good Fund which still benefits Aberdonians.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] During the Wars of Scottish Independence, Aberdeen was under English rule, so Robert the Bruce laid siege to Aberdeen Castle before destroying it in 1308, followed by executing the English garrison.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The city was burned by Edward III of England in 1336, but was rebuilt and extended.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The city was strongly fortified to prevent attacks by neighbouring lords, but the gates were removed by 1770.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's medieval council registers survive from 1398 onwards and are exceptional for their quantity and continuity among surviving Scottish burgh records.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The earliest eight volumes, from 1398 to 1511, have been included in the UNESCO UK Memory of the World Register, and have been edited in a digital edition.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] During the Wars of the Three Kingdoms of 1644 to 1647 the city was plundered by both sides.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] In 1644, it was taken and ransacked by Royalist troops after the Battle of Aberdeen and two years later it was stormed by a Royalist force under the command of the George Gordon, 2nd Marquess of Huntly.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] An outbreak of bubonic plague over 1687 and 1688 killed 8.5% of the population, adding to the economic and demographic damage caused by war.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] In the 18th century, a new Town Hall was built and the first social services appeared with the Aberdeen Infirmary at Woolmanhill in 1739 and the Aberdeen Lunatic Asylum in 1800.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The expensive infrastructure works led to the city becoming bankrupt in 1817 during the Post-Napoleonic depression, an economic downturn immediately after the Napoleonic Wars; but the city's prosperity later recovered.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The increasing economic importance of Aberdeen and the development of the shipbuilding and fishing industries led to the construction of the present harbour including Victoria Dock and the South Breakwater, and the extension of the North Pier.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Gas street lighting arrived in 1824 and an enhanced water supply appeared in 1830 when water was pumped from the Dee to a reservoir in Union Place.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] An underground sewer system replaced open sewers in 1865.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The city absorbed the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside plus the Torry area on the south bank of the Dee in 1891.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Over the course of World War II Aberdeen was attacked 32 times by the German Luftwaffe.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] One of the most devastating attacks was on Wednesday 21 April 1943 when 29 Luftwaffe Dornier 217s flying from Stavanger, Norway attacked the city between the hours of 22:17 and 23:04.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] A total of 98 civilians and 27 servicemen were killed, along with 12,000 houses damaged, after a mixture of 127 Incendiary, High Explosive and Cluster bombs were dropped on the city in one night.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Two books written in 2018 and 2022 using bombing records held in London identified that unexploded bombs from the 1943 raid were found in the 1950s and 1980s making the bombs dropped 129 in total.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Damage from the raid can still be seen in some parts of Aberdeen.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The arms and banner of the city show three silver towers on red.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] This motif dates from at least the time of Robert the Bruce and represents the buildings that stood on the three hills of medieval Aberdeen: Aberdeen Castle on Castle Hill (today's Castlegate); the city gate on Port Hill; and a church on St Catherine's Hill (now levelled).
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] "Bon Accord" is the motto of the city and is French for "Good Agreement".
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Legend tells that its use dates from a password used by Robert the Bruce during the 14th century Wars of Scottish Independence, when he and his men laid siege to the English-held Aberdeen Castle before destroying it in 1308.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] It is still widely present in the city, throughout street names, business names and the city's Bon Accord shopping mall.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The shield in the coat of arms is supported by two leopards.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] A local magazine is called the "Leopard" and, when Union Bridge was widened in the 20th century, small statues of the creature in a sitting position were cast and placed on top of the railing posts (known locally as Kelly's Cats).
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The city's toast is "Happy to meet, sorry to part, happy to meet again".
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] In 2012, HSBC named Aberdeen as a leading business hub and one of eight 'super cities' spearheading the UK's economy, marking it as the only city in Scotland so designated.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] In 2018, Aberdeen was found to be the best city in the UK to start a business in a study released by card payment firm Paymentsense.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen City is one of 32 council areas of Scotland, administered by Aberdeen City Council.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The council meets at Aberdeen Town House and has its main offices in the adjoining Marischal College.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The civic head and chair of the council is the Lord Provost.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The council area is also divided into 30 community council areas, 29 of which had community councils operating as at August 2024.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The first burgh of Aberdeen, covering just the New Aberdeen area near the mouth of the Dee, was created by David I (reigned 1124–1153).
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Neighbouring Old Aberdeen to the north was subsequently made a separate burgh in 1489.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] In 1891 the city boundaries were significantly enlarged, absorbing the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside, plus the Torry area on the south bank of the Dee.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Following the absorption of Torry in 1891, the city boundaries straddled the counties of Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen was made a county of itself in 1899.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] In 1975 the burgh was replaced by the larger City of Aberdeen district within the Grampian region.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Further local government reforms in 1996 replaced the districts and regions created in 1975 with council areas; the pre-1996 City of Aberdeen district became the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] In the Scottish Parliament, the city is represented by three constituencies with different boundaries: Aberdeen Central and Aberdeen Donside are wholly within the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Deeside and North Kincardine includes the North Kincardine ward of Aberdeenshire Council.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] A further seven MSPs are elected as part of the North East Scotland electoral region.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] In the European Parliament the city was represented by six MEPs as part of the all-inclusive Scotland constituency.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is represented in the Parliament of the United Kingdom by two constituencies, Aberdeen North and Aberdeen South, which are wholly within the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Being situated between two river mouths, the city has little natural exposure of bedrock.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The small amount of geophysics done, and occasional building-related exposures, combined with small exposures in the banks of the River Don, suggest that it is actually sited on an inlier of Devonian "Old Red" sandstones and silts.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The city extends to 186 km2 (72 sq mi), and includes the former burghs of Old Aberdeen, New Aberdeen, Woodside and the Torry area to the south of River Dee.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] In 2024, this gave the city a population density of 1,249 inhabitants per square kilometre (3,230/sq mi).
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The city is built on many hills, with the original beginnings of the city growing from Castle Hill, St.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] When compared to mainland Europe, Aberdeen is further north than almost all of Denmark and plenty of southern Sweden, being just south of Gothenburg in terms of latitude.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen features an oceanic climate (Köppen *Cfb*), with far milder winter temperatures than one might expect for its northern location.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] However, statistically speaking, it is still the coldest city in the UK.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] During the winter, especially throughout December, the length of the day is very short, averaging 6 hours and 41 minutes between sunrise and sunset at the winter solstice.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] As winter progresses, the length of the day grows fairly quickly, to 8 hours and 20 minutes by the end of January.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Around summer solstice, the days will be around 18 hours long, having 17 hours and 55 minutes between sunrise and sunset.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] During this time of the year marginal nautical twilight lasts the entire night.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Temperatures at this time of year hover around 17.0 °C (62.6 °F) during the day in most of the urban area, though nearer 16.0 °C (60.8 °F) directly on the coast, and around 18.0 to 19.0 °C (64.4 to 66.2 °F) in the westernmost suburbs.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Two weather stations collect climate data for the area, Aberdeen/Dyce Airport, and Craibstone.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Both are about 4+1⁄2 miles (7 km) to the northwest of the city centre, and given that they are in close proximity to each other, exhibit very similar climatic regimes.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Dyce tends to have marginally warmer daytime temperatures year-round owing to its slightly lower elevation, though it is more susceptible to harsh frosts.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The coldest temperature to occur in recent years was −16.8 °C (1.8 °F) during December 2010, while the following winter, Dyce set a new February high-temperature station record on 28 February 2012 of 17.2 °C (63.0 °F), and a new March high temperature record of 21.6 °C (70.9 °F) on 25 March 2012.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The average temperature of the sea ranges from 6.6 °C (43.9 °F) in March to 13.8 °C (56.8 °F) in August.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen locality population estimate is 198,590 (2020).
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] For the wider settlement of Aberdeen including Cove Bay and Dyce, the population estimate is 220,690 (2020).
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] For Aberdeen City council area, the population estimate is 231,780 (2024).
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] In 1396, the population was about 3,000.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The 2011 census showed fewer young people in Aberdeen, with 16.4% under 16, as opposed to the national average of 19.2%.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] According to the 2011 census Aberdeen is 91.9% white, ethnically, 24.7% were born outside Scotland, higher than the national average of 16%.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Of this population, 7.6% were born in other parts of the UK.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] 8.2% of Aberdonians stated to be from an ethnic minority (non-white) in the 2011 census, with 9,519 (4.3%) being Asian, with 3,385 (1.5%) coming from India and 2,187 (1.0%) being Chinese.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The city has around 5,610 (2.6%) residents of African or Caribbean origin, which is a higher percentage than both Glasgow and Edinburgh.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] In the household, there were 97,013 individual dwellings recorded in the city, of which 61% were privately owned, 9% privately rented and 23% rented from the council.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The most popular type of dwellings are apartments which comprise 49% of residences followed by semi-detached at just below 22%.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The median income of a household in the city is £16,813 (the mean income is £20,292) (2005) which places approximately 18% households in the city below the poverty line (defined as 60% of the mean income).
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Conversely, an Aberdeen postcode has the second highest number of millionaires of any postcode in the UK.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The proportion of people residing in Aberdeen born outside the UK was 21.1% in 2022, compared with 15.9% in 2011 and 6.3% in 2001.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Below are the fifteen largest overseas-born groups in Aberdeen according to the 2022 census, alongside the two previous censuses.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Christianity is the main religion practised in the city.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's largest denominations are the Church of Scotland (through the Presbytery of Aberdeen) and the Roman Catholic Church, both with numerous churches across the city, with the Scottish Episcopal Church having the third-largest number.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The census in 2022 showed that Aberdeen has the highest proportion of non-religious residents of any city in Scotland, with 58% of citizens claiming to have no religion.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] In the Middle Ages, the Kirk of St Nicholas was the only burgh kirk and one of Scotland's largest parish churches.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Like a number of other Scottish kirks, it was subdivided after the Reformation, in this case into the East and West churches.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] At that time, the city also was home to houses of the Carmelites (Whitefriars) and Franciscans (Greyfriars).
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The latter survives in modified form as the chapel of Marischal College.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] St Machar's Cathedral was built twenty years after David I (1124–1153) transferred the pre-Reformation diocese from Mortlach in Banffshire to Old Aberdeen in 1137.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Except the episcopate of William Elphinstone (1484–1511), building progressed slowly.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Gavin Dunbar, who followed him in 1518, completed the structure by adding the two western spires and the southern transept.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] It is now a congregation of the Church of Scotland.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Mary's Cathedral is a Roman Catholic cathedral in Gothic style, erected in 1859.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Andrew's Cathedral serves the Scottish Episcopal Church.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] It was constructed in 1817 as Archibald Simpson's first commission and contains a memorial to the consecration of the first bishop of the Episcopal Church in the United States of America, which took place nearby.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] In 1804, St Peter's Church, the first permanent Roman Catholic church in the city after the Reformation was built.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Numerous other Protestant denominations have a presence in Aberdeen.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The Salvation Army citadel on the Castlegate dominates the view of the east end of Union Street.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] In addition, there is a Unitarian church, established in 1833 and located in Skene Terrace.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Christadelphians have been present in Aberdeen since at least 1844.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Over the years, they have rented space to meet at a number of locations and currently meet in the Inchgarth Community Centre in Garthdee.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] There is also a Quaker meetinghouse on Crown Street, the only purpose built Friends meeting house in Scotland that is still in use today.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] In addition, there are a number of Baptist congregations in the city, and Evangelical congregations have been appearing in significant numbers since the late 2000s.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The city also has two meeting houses of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (LDS Church).
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] There are also four mosques in Aberdeen which serve the Islamic community in the city.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] There is an Orthodox Jewish Synagogue established in 1945.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] There is also a Thai Buddhist temple located in the Hazelhead area of the city.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] There are no formal Hindu buildings, although there is a fortnightly Hindu religious gathering on the first and third Sunday afternoons at Queens Cross Parish church hall.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The University of Aberdeen has a small Baháʼí society.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 217,756 residents aged three and over, 76,650 (35.2%) considered themselves able to speak or read the Scots language.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 217,760 residents aged three and over, 2,919 (1.3%) considered themselves able to speak or read Gaelic.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Traditionally, Aberdeen was home to fishing, textile mills, shipbuilding and paper-making.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] These industries have been largely replaced.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] High technology developments in the electronics design and development industry, research in agriculture and fishing and the oil industry, which have been largely responsible for Aberdeen's economic growth, are now major parts of Aberdeen's economy.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Until the 1970s, most of Aberdeen's leading industries dated from the 18th century; mainly these were textiles, foundry work, shipbuilding and paper-making, the oldest industry in the city, with paper having been first made there in 1694.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Paper-making has reduced in importance since the closures of Donside Paper Mill in 2001 and the Davidson Mill in 2005 leaving the Stoneywood Paper Mill with a workforce of approximately 500.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Textile production ended in 2004 when Richards of Aberdeen closed.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Grey granite was quarried at Rubislaw quarry for more than 300 years, and used for paving setts, kerb and building stones, and monumental and other ornamental pieces.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen granite was used to build the terraces of the Houses of Parliament and Waterloo Bridge in London.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The current owners have begun pumping 40 years of rainwater from the quarry to develop a heritage centre on the site.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] In-shore fishing was once the predominant industry but was surpassed by deep-sea fisheries, which derived a great impetus from improved technologies throughout the 20th century.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Catches have fallen because of overfishing and the use of the harbour by oil support vessels, and so although still an important fishing port it is now eclipsed by the more northerly ports of Peterhead and Fraserburgh.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The Fisheries Research Services are headquartered in Aberdeen, and there is a marine research laboratory there.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is well regarded for the agricultural and soil research carried out at The James Hutton Institute (formerly the Macaulay Land Use Research Institute), which has close links to the city's two universities.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The Rowett Research Institute is a world-renowned research centre for studies into food and nutrition located in Aberdeen.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] It has produced three Nobel laureates and there is a high concentration of life scientists working in the city.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] As oil reserves in the North Sea decrease, there is an effort to rebrand Aberdeen as the **energy capital of Europe** rather than the oil capital, and there is interest in the development of new energy sources, and technology transfer from oil into renewable energy and other industries is underway.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The "Energetica" initiative led by Scottish Enterprise has been designed to accelerate this process.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has become a major world centre for undersea petroleum technology.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen had been a major maritime centre throughout the 19th century, when a group of local entrepreneurs launched the first steam-powered trawler.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The steam trawling industry expanded and by 1933 Aberdeen was Scotland's top fishing port, employing nearly 3,000 men with 300 vessels sailing from its harbour.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] By the time oil was coming on stream, much of the trawling fleet had relocated to Peterhead.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Geologists had speculated about oil and gas in the North Sea since the middle of the 20th century, but tapping its deep and inhospitable waters was another story.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] With the Middle Eastern oil sheiks becoming more aware of the political and economic power of their oil reserves and government threats of rationing, the industry began to consider the North Sea as a viable source of oil.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Exploration commenced in the 1960s and the first major find in the British sector was in November 1970 in the Forties field, 110 miles (180 km) east of Aberdeen.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] By late 1975, after years of intense construction, the necessary infrastructure was in place.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Oil flowed through the Forties pipeline system directly to the refinery at far-away Grangemouth.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] In 2011, the Centre for Cities named Aberdeen as the best-placed city for growth in Britain, as the country looked to emerge from the recent economic downturn.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] With energy still providing the backbone of the local economy, recent years have seen very large new investment in the North Sea owing to rising oil prices and favourable government tax incentives.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] This has led to several oil majors and independents building new global offices in the city.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Five of Scotland's top ten businesses are based in Aberdeen with a collective turnover of £14 billion, yielding a profit in excess of £2.4 billion.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Alongside this 29 of Scotland's top 100 businesses are located in Aberdeen with an employment rate of 77.9%, making it the second highest UK city for employment.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Figures released in 2016 ranked Aberdeen as having the second highest number of patents processed per person in the UK.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The traditional shopping streets are Union Street and George Street, now complemented by shopping centres, including the Bon Accord Centre and the Trinity Shopping Centre.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] A £190 million retail development, Union Square, reached completion in late September/early October 2009.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Major retail parks away from the city centre include the Berryden Retail Park, the Kittybrewster Retail Park and the Beach Boulevard Retail Park.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Market has been rebuilt twice, but closed in 2020.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] In March 2004, Aberdeen was awarded Fairtrade City status by the Fairtrade Foundation.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's architecture is known for its principal use during the Victorian era of granite, which has led to its local nickname of the Granite City.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] In Castle Street, a continuation eastwards of Union Street, is the new Aberdeen Town House, a very prominent landmark in Aberdeen, built between 1868 and 1873 to a design by Peddie and Kinnear.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Alexander Marshall Mackenzie's extension to Marischal College on Broad Street, opened by King Edward VII in 1906, created the second largest granite building in the world (after the Escorial, Madrid).
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has long been famous for its 45 parks and gardens, and citywide floral displays which include two million roses, eleven million daffodils and three million crocuses.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The city has won the Royal Horticultural Society's Britain in Bloom 'Best City' award ten times, the overall Scotland in Bloom competition twenty times and the large city category every year since 1968.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] However, despite recent spurious reports, Aberdeen has never been banned from the Britain in Bloom competition.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The city won the 2006 Scotland in Bloom "Best City" award along with the International Cities in Bloom award.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The suburb of Dyce also won the Small Towns award.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Duthie Park opened in 1883 on the north bank of the River Dee.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] It was named after and given to the city by Miss Elizabeth Crombie Duthie of Ruthrieston in 1881.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Hazlehead Park, is large and forested, and located on the outskirts of the city.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Johnston Gardens is a small park of one hectare in the west end of the city.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] In 2002, the garden was named the best garden in the British Islands.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Seaton Park, formerly the grounds of a private house, is on the edge of the grounds of St Machar's Cathedral and was acquired for the city in 1947.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has hosted several theatres throughout its history, some of which have been converted or destroyed.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Today, all railway services to the south run via Dundee.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The faster main line from Aberdeen to Perth via Forfar and Strathmore closed in 1967, as a result of the Beeching cuts; the faster main line from Perth to Edinburgh via Glenfarg also closed subsequently in 1970.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] A second station, at Dyce, serves the north of the city centre; it is on the Aberdeen–Inverness line.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] First Aberdeen operates the majority of city bus services, as the successor to Grampian Regional Transport (GRT) and Aberdeen Corporation Tramways.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Secondary operators include Stagecoach Bluebird and Stagecoach South Scotland.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is the global headquarters of parent company FirstGroup, having grown from the GRT Group.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] First is still based at the former Aberdeen Tramways depot on King Street, which has now been redeveloped into a new headquarters and bus depot.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] On 18 April 2025, the "Aberdeen Adventurer" tour bus scheme ran by McGill's Bus Services was launched with 10 stops around the city on a 75-minute loop.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Stops include King's College, Pittodrie Stadium and the Aberdeen Art Gallery with the service due to end on 20 September 2026.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen International Airport (ABZ), sited in Dyce in the north of the city, serves domestic and international destinations in France, the Netherlands, Spain, Ireland and Scandinavian countries.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The heliport, which serves the oil industry and rescue services, is one of the world's busiest commercial heliports.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is connected to the UK's National Cycle Network; it has a track to the south, connecting to cities including Dundee and Edinburgh, and one to the north that forks about 10 miles (15 km) from the city into two different tracks heading to Inverness and Fraserburgh respectively.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Two popular shared-use paths, along old railway lines, are the Deeside Way to Banchory (which will eventually connect to Ballater) and the Formartine and Buchan Way to Ellon, both used by a mixture of cyclists, walkers and occasionally horses.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] In May 2026, a self-service e-bike hire scheme was introduced in Aberdeen, operated by Voi Technology.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Some 350 bikes are available on a pay-as-you-go basis.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The scheme replaced an earlier bike hire scheme which was operated between 2022 and 2024 by *The Big Issue* and Sharebike but which was scrapped because of funding issues as well as vandalism.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Harbour is important as the largest in the north of Scotland and serves the ferry route to Orkney and Shetland.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Established in 1136, the harbour has been referred to as the "oldest business in Britain".
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The Dee Estuary, Aberdeen's harbour, started out as a fishing port, moving on to steam trawlers and serving the oil industry; it is now a major port of departure for the Baltic and Scandinavia.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has two universities, the ancient University of Aberdeen, and Robert Gordon University, a modern university often referred to as RGU.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has a high proportion of students of 11.5%, higher than the national average of 7%.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The University of Aberdeen began as King's College, Aberdeen, which was founded in 1495 by William Elphinstone (1431–1514), Bishop of Aberdeen and Chancellor of Scotland.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Marischal College, a separate institution, was founded in New Aberdeen by George Keith, fifth Earl Marischal of Scotland in 1593.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] These institutions were merged by the Universities (Scotland) Act 1858 to form the University of Aberdeen.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The university is the fifth oldest in the English-speaking world and offers degrees in a full range of disciplines.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Its main campus is in Old Aberdeen in the north of the city and it currently has approximately 14,000 students.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The university's debating society is the oldest in Scotland, founded in 1848 as the King's College Debating Society.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Today, Aberdeen is consistently ranked among the top 200 universities in the world and is ranked within the top 20 universities in the United Kingdom.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen was also named the 2019 Scottish University of the Year by The Times and Sunday Times Good University Guide.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] In early 2022, Aberdeen opened the Science Teaching Hub.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Robert Gordon's College (originally Robert Gordon's Hospital) was founded in 1750 by the merchant Robert Gordon, grandson of the map maker Robert Gordon of Straloch, and was further endowed in 1816 by Alexander Simpson of Collyhill.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Originally devoted to the instruction and maintenance of the sons of poor burgesses of guild and trade in the city, it was reorganised in 1881 as a day and night school for secondary and technical education.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] In 1903, the vocational education component of the college was designated a Central Institution and was renamed as the Robert Gordon Institute of Technology in 1965.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] In 1992, university status was awarded and it became Robert Gordon University.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The university has expanded and developed significantly in recent years, and was named Best Modern University in the UK for 2012 by *The Sunday Times*.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] It was previously *The Sunday Times* Scottish University of the Year for 2011, primarily because of its record on graduate employment.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is also home to two artistic schools: Gray's School of Art, founded in 1886, which is one of the oldest established colleges of art in the UK.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Scott Sutherland School of Architecture and Built Environment, was one of the first architectural schools to have its training courses recognised by the Royal Institute of British Architects.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Both are now part of Robert Gordon University and are based at its Garthdee campus.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] North East Scotland College has several campuses in the city and offers a wide variety of part-time and full-time courses leading to several different qualifications in science.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The Scottish Agricultural College is based just outside Aberdeen, on the Craibstone Estate.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] This is situated beside the roundabout for Aberdeen Airport on the A96.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The college provides three services—Learning, Research and Consultancy.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The college features many land-based courses such as Agriculture, Countryside Management, Sustainable Environmental Management and Rural Business Management.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] There are a variety of courses from diplomas to master's degrees.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The Marine Laboratory Aberdeen, which specialises in fisheries, Macaulay Land Use Research Institute (soil science), and the Rowett Research Institute (animal nutrition) are some other higher education institutions.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen College of Performing Arts also provides full-time Drama and Musical Theatre training at Further Education level.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] There are currently 15 secondary schools and 54 primary schools which are run by the city council.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] There are a number of private schools in Aberdeen: Robert Gordon's College, Albyn School, St Margaret's School for Girls, the International School of Aberdeen and a Waldorf/Steiner School.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] State secondary schools in Aberdeen include Aberdeen Grammar School, Bridge of Don Academy, Bucksburn Academy, Cults Academy, Dyce Academy, Harlaw Academy, Hazlehead Academy, Lochside Academy, Northfield Academy, Oldmachar Academy and St Machar Academy.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p01] Independent primary and secondary schools in Aberdeen include Albyn School, Robert Gordon's College, St Margaret's School for Girls, and the International School of Aberdeen.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] The city has a wide range of cultural activities, amenities, and museums, and is regularly visited by Scotland's National Arts Companies.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] It was awarded the Nicholson Trophy for the best-kept town at the Britain in Bloom contest in 1975.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Art Gallery houses a collection of Impressionist, Victorian, Scottish and 20th-century British paintings as well as collections of silver and glass.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] It also includes The Alexander Macdonald Bequest, a collection of late 19th-century works donated by the museum's first benefactor and a constantly changing collection of contemporary work and regular visiting exhibitions.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Art Gallery reopened in 2019 after a four-year refurbishment costing £34.6m.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Maritime Museum, located in Shiprow, tells the story of Aberdeen's links with the sea from the days of sail and clipper ships to the latest oil and gas exploration technology.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] It includes an 8.5-metre-high (28 ft) model of the Murchison oil production platform and a 19th-century assembly taken from Rattray Head lighthouse Provost Ross' House is the second oldest dwelling house in the city.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] It was built in 1593 and became the residence of Provost John Ross of Arnage in 1702.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] The house retains some original medieval features, including a kitchen, fireplaces and beam-and-board ceilings.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] The Gordon Highlanders Museum tells the story of one of Scotland's best known regiments.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] Provost Skene's House on Flourmill Lane dates from 1545 and is the oldest surviving townhouse in the city.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] It reopened in October 2021 after significant refurbishment costing £3.8m.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] One of the new exhibitions is a Hall of Heroes featuring 100 Aberdonians who have made a significant contribution to the city.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] The Tollbooth Museum on the Castlegate (currently closed to visitors) is a former jail, which first opened as a public museum in 1995.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Treasure Hub is a storage facility for Aberdeen Museums and Galleries containing over 100,000 items.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] The store is open for infrequent tours, for example as part of Doors Open Day.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] Marischal Museum holds the principal collections of the University of Aberdeen, comprising some 80,000 items in the areas of fine art, Scottish history and archaeology, and European, Mediterranean and Near Eastern archaeology.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] The permanent displays and reference collections are augmented by regular temporary exhibitions, and since its closure to the public it now has a virtual online presence It closed to the public in 2008.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] The King's Museum acts as the main museum of the university now.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Student Show, performed annually without interruption since 1921, under the auspices of the Aberdeen Students' Charities Campaign, is the longest-running of its kind in the United Kingdom.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] It is written, produced and performed by students and graduates of Aberdeen's universities and higher education institutions.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] Since 1929—other than on a handful of occasions—it has been staged at His Majesty's Theatre.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] National festivals which visited Aberdeen in 2012 included the British Science Festival in September, hosted by the University of Aberdeen but with events also taking place at Robert Gordon University and at other venues across the city.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] In February 2012 the University of Aberdeen also hosted the Inter Varsity Folk Dance Festival, the longest-running folk festival in the United Kingdom.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Spectra, an annual light festival hosted in different locations across the city.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Nuart, a festival showcasing street art around the city.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] In 2020, the WayWORD Festival was launched by the University of Aberdeen WORD centre for creative writing.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] This yearly programme celebrates the arts through readings, performances, workshops and discussion panels.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] There have been many notable headliners including Val McDermid, Irvine Welsh and Douglas Stuart (writer).
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] Galas are held annually throughout the city, the most notable being the Culter Gala, which is usually held on the last Saturday of May.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] The local dialect of Lowland Scots is often known as Doric and is spoken not just in the city, but across the northeast of Scotland.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] It differs somewhat from other Scots dialects: most noticeable are the pronunciation "f" for what is normally written "wh" and "ee" for what in standard English would usually be written "oo" (Scots "ui").
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] Every year the annual Doric Festival takes place in Aberdeenshire to celebrate the history of the north-east's language.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Scotland's oldest newspaper the *Press and Journal*, a local and regional newspaper first published in 1747.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] The *Press and Journal* and its sister paper the tabloid *Evening Express* are printed six days a week by Aberdeen Journals.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] There was one free newspaper, the *Aberdeen Citizen*.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] BBC Scotland has a network studio production base in the city's Beechgrove area, and BBC Aberdeen produces *The Beechgrove Potting Shed* for radio while Tern Television produces *The Beechgrove Garden*.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] The city is also home to STV North (formerly Grampian Television), which produces the regional news programmes such as *STV News at Six*, as well as local commercials.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] The station, based at Craigshaw Business Park in Tullos, was based at larger studios in Queens Cross from September 1961 until June 2003.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] Music venues include the Music Hall and the P&J Live.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen region has given its name to a number of dishes, including the Aberdeen buttery (also known as "rowie") and Aberdeen Sausage.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] In 2015, a study was published in The Scotsman which analysed the presence of branded fast food outlets in Scotland.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] Of the ten towns and cities analysed, Aberdeen was found to have the lowest per capita concentration, with just 0.12 stores per 1,000 inhabitants.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] The public health service in Scotland, NHS Scotland provides for the people of Aberdeen through the NHS Grampian health board.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] Albyn Hospital is a private hospital located in the west end of the city.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen City Council is responsible for city-owned infrastructure which is paid for by a mixture of Council Tax and income from the Scottish Government.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] Infrastructure and services run by the council include: nursery, primary and secondary education, roads, clearing snow in winter, city wardens, maintaining parks, refuse collection, economic development, public analyst, public mortuary, street cleaning and street lighting.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] Infrastructure in private hands includes electricity, gas and telecoms.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] Water and sewerage services are provided by Scottish Water.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] The first ever recorded game of football, was outlined by teacher David Wedderburn in his book "Vocabula" written in 1633, during his time teaching at Aberdeen Grammar School.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] There is one Aberdeen-based football club in the SPFL.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] (The Dons) play in the Scottish Premiership at Pittodrie Stadium.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] The club won the European Cup Winners Cup and the European Super Cup in 1983, the Scottish Premier League Championship four times (1955, 1980, 1984 and 1985), and the Scottish Cup eight times (1947, 1970, 1982, 1983, 1984, 1986, 1990 and 2025).
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] Under the management of Alex Ferguson, Aberdeen was a major force in British football during the 1980s.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] Under the management of McInnes the team won the 2014 Scottish League Cup and followed it up with a second-place league finish for the first time in more than 20 years in the following season.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] But it was over the last few seasons that results stagnated and McInnes was replaced by former Aberdeen and Newcastle player Stephen Glass.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] Cove Rangers, as of season 2024-25 play in League One, at the Balmoral Stadium in the suburb of Cove Bay.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] Cove won the Highland Football League championship in 2001, 2008, 2009, 2013 and 2019, winning the League Two play-offs in 2019 and earning promotion.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] At the point at which the 2019/20 League Two season was curtailed due to the COVID-19 pandemic, Cove were sitting top of the League Two table and were promoted as Champions.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] Other local teams include Banks o'Dee who play at Spain Park in the Highland Football League and members of the SJFA North Region; Culter, Dyce, Stoneywood Parkvale, Glentanar, Sunnybank Hall Russell United, Bridge of Don Thistle and Hermes.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen hosted Caledonia Reds, a Scottish rugby team, before they merged with the Glasgow Warriors in 1998.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] In 2005 the President of the SRU said it was hoped eventually to establish a professional team in Aberdeen.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] In November 2008 the city hosted a rugby international at Pittodrie between Scotland and Canada, with Scotland winning 41–0.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] In November 2010 the city once again hosted a rugby international at Pittodrie between Scotland and Samoa, with Scotland winning 19–16.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Warriors rugby league team play in the Rugby League Conference Division One.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] The Warriors also run Under 15's and 17's teams.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Grammar School won the Saltire Schools Cup in 2011.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] The Royal Aberdeen Golf Club, founded in 1780 is the sixth oldest golf club in the world, and hosted the Senior British Open in 2005, and the amateur team event the Walker Cup in 2011.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] Royal Aberdeen also hosted the Scottish Open in 2014, won by Justin Rose.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] The club has a second course, and there are public golf courses at Auchmill, Balnagask, Hazlehead and King's Links.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] There are new courses planned for the area, including world-class facilities with major financial backing, the city and shire are set to become important in golf tourism.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] In Summer 2012, Donald Trump opened a new state of the art golf course at Menie, just north of the city, as the Trump International Golf Links, Scotland.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] Ice hockey in Aberdeen boasts a history that began in the early 20th century.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Glaciarium on Forbesfield Road became a hub for games, featuring teams like the Grammar School Former Pupils and the Aberdeen Ice Hockey Club.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] However, the sport all but died out with the onset of WW1.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] The sport was revived in the city with the opening of the Linx Ice Arena in 1992.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Lynx plays in the Scottish National League and is based at the Linx Ice Arena.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] Founded in 2005, they won back to back regular season titles in 2022-23 and 2023–24 and won the play-off championship in 2015-16 and again in 2024–25.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] They regularly sell out home games and are the second best supported sports team in the city after Aberdeen FC.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] The City of Aberdeen Swim Team (COAST) was based in Northfield swimming pool, but since the opening of the Aberdeen Aquatics Centre in 2014, it is now based there, as it has a 50 m pool as opposed to the 25 m pool at Northfield.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] The team comprises several smaller swimming clubs and has enjoyed success throughout Scotland and in international competitions.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] Three of the team's swimmers qualified for the 2006 Commonwealth Games.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] There are four boat clubs that row on the River Dee: Aberdeen Boat Club (ABC), Aberdeen Schools Rowing Association (ASRA), Aberdeen University Boat Club (AUBC) and Robert Gordon University Boat Club (RGUBC).
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] The city has one national league side, Stoneywood-Dyce.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] Local "Grades" cricket has been played in Aberdeen since 1884.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeenshire were the 2009 and 2014 Scottish National Premier League and Scottish Cup Champions.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen University Shinty Club (Scottish Gaelic: Club Camanachd Oilthigh Obar Dheathain) is the oldest constituted shinty club in the world, dating back to 1861.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] The city council operates public tennis courts in various parks including an indoor tennis centre at Westburn Park.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] The Beach Leisure Centre is home to a climbing wall, gymnasium and a swimming pool.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] There are numerous swimming pools dotted around the city notably the largest, the Bon Accord Baths which closed down in 2008.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] In common with many other major towns and cities in the UK, Aberdeen has an active roller derby league, Granite City Roller Derby.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Roughnecks American football club is a new team that started in 2012 and is the first team that Aberdeen has witnessed since the Granite City Oilers that began in 1986 and were wound up in the mid-1990s.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Oilers Floorball Club was founded in 2007.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] The club initially attracted a range of experienced Scandinavian and other European players who were studying in Aberdeen.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] Since their formation, Aberdeen Oilers have played in the British Floorball Northern League and went on to win the league in the 2008/09 season.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] The club played a major role in setting up a ladies league in Scotland.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] The Oilers' ladies team ended up second in the first ladies league season (2008/09).
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] One of the earliest known disasters is the Storegga Slide in the mesolithic period in 6225–6170 BCE which caused tsunami waves to hit North sea coastal areas, with wave heights of 3-6 meters in the north east Scotland areas.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] In 1876, the River Dee ferryboat disaster took place when 32 people drowned in the mouth of the River Dee.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] The 20th century includes a World War II disaster when in 1943, a Luftwaffe raid dropped 129 bombs on Aberdeen resulting in 125 deaths..
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] In 1964, a typhoid outbreak occurred with 400 cases and three fatalities.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] In 1983, the Aberdeen taxi driver George Murdoch was killed, the murder case is unsolved.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] In modern time, accidents have been related with offshore drilling.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] In 1988, the oil platform Piper Alpha, located 190 km north-east of Aberdeen, exploded and collapsed, killing 165.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] The accident is the worst ever offshore oil and gas disaster in terms of lives lost.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] Hazlehead Park contains a memorial to the crew. .
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] In 1995, Bristow Helicopters Flight 56C was struck by lightning and emergency landed in the sea.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] The 18 crew and passengers on board survived.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] In 2009, the Bond Offshore Helicopters Flight 85N crashed 20 km north-east of Peterhead, while returning from an oil platform to Aberdeen Airport.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-p02] Johnston Gardens contains a memorial to the deceased.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The **University of Aberdeen** (abbreviated ***Aberd.*** in post-nominals; Scottish Gaelic: *Oilthigh Obar Dheathain*) is a public research university in Aberdeen, Scotland.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] It was founded in 1495 when William Elphinstone, Bishop of Aberdeen and Chancellor of Scotland, petitioned Pope Alexander VI on behalf of King James IV to establish King's College, making it one of Scotland's four ancient universities and the fifth-oldest university in the English-speaking world.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Along with the universities of St Andrews, Glasgow, and Edinburgh, the university was part of the Scottish Enlightenment during the 18th century.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The university as it is currently constituted was formed in 1860 by a merger between King's College and Marischal College, a second university founded in 1593 as a Protestant alternative to the former.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The university's iconic buildings act as symbols of wider Aberdeen, particularly Marischal College in the city centre and the crown steeple of King's College in Old Aberdeen.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] There are two campuses; the predominantly utilised King's College campus dominates the section of the city known as Old Aberdeen, which is approximately two miles north of the city centre.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Although the original site of the university's foundation, most academic buildings apart from the King's College Chapel and Quadrangle were constructed in the 20th century during a period of significant expansion.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The university's Foresterhill campus is next to Aberdeen Royal Infirmary and houses the School of Medicine and Dentistry as well as the School of Medical Sciences.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Together these buildings form one of Europe's largest health campuses.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The annual income of the institution for 2024–25 was £257.2 million of which £54.2 million was from research grants and contracts, with an expenditure of £262.5 million.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Aberdeen has educated a wide range of notable alumni, and the university played key roles in the Scottish Reformation, Scottish Enlightenment, and the Scottish Renaissance.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Five Nobel laureates have since been associated with the university: two in Chemistry, one in Physiology or Medicine, one in Physics, and one in Peace.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] There appears to have existed in Old Aberdeen, from a very early period, a *studium generate,* or university, attached to the episcopal chapter of the See of Aberdeen.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] It seems that James was keen to ensure that Scotland had as many universities as England at the time, and it was to possess all the privileges enjoyed by those of Paris and Bologna, two of the most highly favoured in Europe.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The university, modelled on that of the University of Paris and intended principally as a law school, soon became the most famous and popular of the Scots seats of learning, largely due to the prestige of Elphinstone and his friend, Hector Boece, the first principal appointed in 1500.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Its aim was to train doctors, teachers and clergy who would serve the communities of northern Scotland, as well as lawyers and administrators for the Scottish Crown.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] It was a collegiate foundation with 36 full-time staff and students and walls protecting it from the outside world.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] In 1497 the college established the first chair of medicine in the English-speaking world.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The first book (there was no printing press in Scotland at the time) to be printed in Edinburgh and in Scotland was the Aberdeen Breviary, which was written by both Elphinstone and Boece in 1509.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Following the Scottish Reformation in 1560, King's College was purged of its Roman Catholic staff but in other respects was largely resistant to change.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] George Keith, the fifth Earl Marischal, was a moderniser within the college and supportive of the reforming ideas of Peter Ramus and Andrew Melville.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] In April 1593 he founded a second university in the 'New Town', Marischal College.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] It is also possible the founding of the Fraserburgh University in nearby Fraserburgh by Sir Alexander Fraser, a business rival of Keith, was instrumental in its creation.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Aberdeen was highly unusual at this time for having two universities in one city: as 20th-century university prospectuses observed, Aberdeen had the same number as existed in England at the time (the University of Oxford and University of Cambridge).
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Initially, Marischal College offered the principal of King's College a role in selecting its academics, but this was refused – the first blow in a developing rivalry.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Marischal College, in the commercial heart of the city (rather than the ancient but much smaller collegiate enclave of Old Aberdeen), was quite different in nature and outlook.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] For example, it was more integrated into the life of the city, such as allowing students to live outwith the college.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The two rival colleges often clashed, sometimes in court, but also in brawls between students on the streets of Aberdeen.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Duncan Liddell endowed the first chair in mathematics at Marischal College in 1613, but the first professor was not appointed until 1626.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] As the institutions put aside their differences, a process of attempted (but unsuccessful) mergers began in the 17th century.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] During this time, both colleges made notable intellectual contributions to the Scottish Enlightenment.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Both colleges supported the Jacobite rebellion and following the defeat of the 1715 rising were largely purged by the authorities of their academics and officials.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The nearest the two colleges had come to full union was as the Caroline University of Aberdeen, a merger initiated by Charles I in 1641, which united the two colleges for twenty years.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Following the civil conflicts of the Wars of the Three Kingdoms, a more complete unification was attempted following the ratification of Parliament by Oliver Cromwell during the interregnum in 1654.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] This united university survived until the Restoration whereby all laws made during this period were rescinded by Charles II and the two colleges reverted to independent status.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Charles I is still recognised as one of the university's founders, due to his part in creating the Caroline University and his benevolence towards King's College.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The Aberdeen Philosophical Society (known locally as the Wise Club) was created by Thomas Reid, George Campbell, David Skene, John Gregory, John Stewart, and Robert Traill, and held its first meeting in the Old Red Lion Inn on 12 January 1758.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] From its inception, the society was an intimate, private body whose members were drawn exclusively from the learned professions, and this feature differentiated it from the more open and socially inclusive societies like the Glasgow Literary Society or the Select Society of Edinburgh.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Over 133 papers were given and discussed at the meeting, and many of these formed the basis of books subsequently published.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The society was eventually disbanded in March 1773.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The society and its individual members played a key role in the Scottish Enlightenment, and it was the most important forum for the promotion of enlightened thought and values in Aberdeen.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The Free Church of Scotland founded Christ's College in Aberdeen in 1843 for the training of ministers.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] An extravagant Gothic building, with a commanding oriel window and tower, was erected for the college at the western end of Union Street in 1850.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Linked to the college was a museum and library (containing 17,000 volumes).
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Following the church reunion of 1929, Christ's College became a Church of Scotland college and was integrated into the University of Aberdeen.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The college building is no longer used by either the church or the university, and the college is contained completely within the buildings of King's College, maintaining its own divinity library.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The university hosted its first meeting of the British Science Association in 1859.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Having no suitable meeting place to host the meeting, the town raised the money themselves by personal subscription and built the Music Hall.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] It was capable of holding about 2,500 people and so successful was the meeting that associate membership, necessary to gain access to the proceedings, had to be capped.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Prominent among the local organisers were Professors James Clerk Maxwell (Natural Philosophy) and James Nicol (Geology) of Marischal College.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Prince Albert, the Prince Consort, took on the role of president for the year.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The young Maxwell himself, still only 28, spoke on three different subjects, one being a presentation of his newly discovered law of molecular velocities in a gas.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The 'Maxwell distribution law', as it is now known, is the law of physics with the strongest Aberdeen connection.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] In addition, Sir Charles Lyell, president of the Geological Section of the British Academy, and a champion of Charles Darwin's work, made one of the first announcements that Darwin had undertaken a body of work on evolution and was about to release his findings.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The organisers felt that they might be risking something in holding the meeting much further north than they had done before but in the event the Aberdeen meeting was the most well attended the BA had ever had.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Further unsuccessful suggestions for union were brought about throughout the 18th and early 19th centuries.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] William Ogilvie, known as the Rebel Professor, proposed a paper on the union and reform of the two colleges in 1787, but the proposals were rejected by seven (known as the 'seven wise Masters') out of ten professors at King's.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The evolving examination system and university research now required much higher academic standards from the students.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The two colleges in Aberdeen merged on 15 September 1860 in accordance with the Universities (Scotland) Act 1858, which also created a new medical school at Marischal College.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The 1858 Act of Parliament stated the "*united University shall take rank among the Universities of Scotland as from the date of erection of King's College and University.*" The university is thus Scotland's third oldest and the United Kingdom's fifth oldest university.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The transference of the arts classes from Marischal to King's College required the extension of King's at the cost of £20,000.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] This included the rebuilding of two sides of the quadrangle for the class-rooms (1862) and the erection of the library (1870), which for many years had occupied the nave of the chapel.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] In 1873, university students voted against university degrees being open to women.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] However, all faculties were open to women in 1892, and in 1894 the first 20 matriculated females began their studies at the university.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Four women graduated in arts by 1898, and by the following year, women made up a quarter of the faculty.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The closing of the quadrangle of Marischal College was completed during the university's quatercentenary in 1906, which was officially opened by Edward VII and Alexandra, and which saw some of the most extravagant celebrations and expressions of civic pride ever demonstrated in Aberdeen.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Four days of festivities took place across the city, which included church services, banquets, torchlight processions, and fireworks displays.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] In all, the cost of the four days of festivities was the modern equivalent of £1.34 million.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The ceremony saw the granting of honorary degrees to over a hundred public and academic figures from across the academic world.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] In an extravagant display of luxury, Lord Strathcona, the then chancellor of the university, spent £8518 in entertaining around 2500 invited guests in a tent specially designed for the occasion.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] After having received an honorary degree (LLD) in 1905, Thomas Hardy celebrated Aberdeen as 'a university which can claim in my opinion to an exceptional degree that breadth of view & openness of mind that all Universities profess to cultivate, but many stifle'.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Hardy wrote a poem for a special number of the student publication, *Alma Mater*, in celebration of the quatercentenary of the university.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] In the 20th century, the university expanded greatly, particularly at King's College.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] New buildings were constructed on the land around King's College throughout the 20th century.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Initially, these were built to match the ancient buildings (e.g. the New King's lecture rooms and Elphinstone Hall), but later ones from the 1960s onward were constructed in brutalist style.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Meanwhile, the Foresterhill campus began to train medical students in the 1930s next to Aberdeen Royal Infirmary.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Following extensive fundraising, a £57 million new university library (the Sir Duncan Rice Library) opened in autumn 2011 at the King's College campus to replace the outgrown Queen Mother Library and was officially opened by the Queen in September 2012.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Today, most students spend most of their time in modern buildings which provide up-to-date facilities for teaching, research and other activities such as dining.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] However, the old buildings at King's College are still in use as lecture and tutorial rooms and accommodation for various academic departments.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] In February 2020, the Scottish Funding Council (SFC) found that in approving a financial settlement agreement with the former principal Sir Ian Diamond, the university failed to make best use of public funds or exercise good governance.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] As a result of the investigation, the university was ordered to repay £119,000 of grant finance to the SFC and undertake an externally facilitated examination of its governance and culture.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] On 5 December 2023 it was announced that a working group, chaired by Professor Karl Leydecker, had been set up to look at the future of teaching of modern languages at the university.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] It was looking at three options, "all of which involve the end of single honours French, Gaelic, German and Spanish", and was engaging in consultation with student and faculty.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] It was stated that departmental "income does not cover even the direct costs of staff delivering Modern Languages provision before any central costs ... leading to a projected deficit for Modern Languages of £1.64m in 2023/24." The financial statements were contested by staff and UCU.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] At an online meeting of the University Senate on 6 December, senators voted 78–15 in favour of a motion which "called for an immediate halt in the consultation process until an overall plan is presented in detail to Senate for appropriate scrutiny." Five senators abstained.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] On 8 December, *The Gaudie* reported that staff had been sent 'Risk of Redundancy' letters which stated that staff who are made redundant would receive four months pay.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] A group of academics from the department released a statement which described the proposed changes as "institutional vandalism".
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] A public petition to save Modern Languages gained over 18,600 signatures.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] After the submission of two motions calling to protect languages degrees at the University of Aberdeen, a debate took place in Scottish Parliament, where the university was urged to explore alternative options.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] EU consulates also spoke out in favour of the languages programmes., as well as scome of Scotland's best-known folk music starts.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The local UCU branch successfully balloted for strike action at the university, in support of Modern Languages degrees.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Staff-led business proposals were positively received and the consultation on Modern Languages was ended in March 2024 with the removal of risk of compulsory redundancies.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The university's main campus is at King's College in Old Aberdeen, where the original buildings are still in use in addition to many 20th-century buildings.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] A second campus at Foresterhill accommodates the School of Medicine, Medical Science and Nutrition.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] In addition, there are smaller facilities at other sites such as the Royal Cornhill Hospital to the west of the city centre, and the Rowett Institute in Bucksburn.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The King's College campus covers an area of some 35 hectares around the ancient King's College buildings and the High Street.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] It hosts around two-thirds of the university's built estate and most student facilities, and lies 2 miles north of Aberdeen city centre.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The university does not own all the buildings on the "campus" which also include private houses, shops and businesses (although many of these rely heavily on custom from the university community) and it is best thought of as a district of the city dominated by the university.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] It can be reached from the city centre by bus routes 1, 2, 13, 19 and 20 operated by First Aberdeen and from northern Aberdeenshire or Aberdeen bus station by various routes operated by Stagecoach Bluebird.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The historic King's College buildings form a quadrangle with an interior court, two sides of which have been rebuilt and expanded with a library wing in the 19th century.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The Crown Tower and the chapel, the oldest parts, date from around 1500.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The original foundation contained the chapel, the Great Hall and living accommodation, with its own kitchen and brewery, a well in the quadrangle, and a college garden to provide herbs and vegetables.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The Grammar School was just outside the walls, in front of the college.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The Crown Tower is surmounted by a structure about 40 ft (12 m) high, consisting of a six-sided lantern and Imperial crown, both sculptured, and resting on the intersections of two arched ornamental slips rising from the four corners of the top of the tower.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] This crown, also known as the "Crown of Kings", frequently acts as a symbol of the university.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The choir of the chapel contains original oak-canopied stalls, miserere seats, and lofty open screens in the French flamboyant style.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] They were preserved by the college's Principal during the Reformation, who fought off local barons who had attacked the nearby St Machar's Cathedral.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The Cromwell Tower, created between 1658 and 1662 opposite the Crown Tower, was originally built as residential accommodation, but an observatory was built on top in 1826.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The library wing was converted into an exhibition and conference venue in the 1990s and today also houses the university's Business School.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The first of the modern age of construction in the King's campus began with the construction in 1913 of the New Building (now known as *"New King's"*), largely in a similar architectural style to the old buildings.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] A large manse located on the lawn opposite King's College was removed before the First World War.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] New King's groups to form a yet larger quadrangle-like green for the campus also bordered by the High Street, King's and Elphinstone Hall, a traditional 1930 replacement for the Great Hall.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The Elphinstone Hall was subsequently used as a dining facility but is now used for graduations, examinations, fairs, and other large university events.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] However, most students and staff spend relatively little time in these historic buildings, with a large number of modern ones housing most facilities and academic departments.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Most date from the second half of the 20th century.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Some of these echo the existing architecture of Old Aberdeen, such as the Fraser Noble Building with its distinctive concrete crown designed to resemble the one adorning King's College.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Other buildings were constructed of stone in the 1950s (e.g. the Taylor Building and Meston Building).
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] A number of other buildings are designed in the brutalist style, such as the Arts Lecture Theatre and adjoining William Guild Building, opened in 1969 to house the School of Psychology.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Also on the site is the Cruickshank Botanic Garden which was presented to the university in 1899 and is open to the public.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The Powis Gateway forms the east gate and archway from College Bounds, Old Aberdeen.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] These oriental style towers with minarets have provoked much interest over the years.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] At one time there was a portrait of John Leslie dressed in Turkish costume, on the walls of Powis House, but there is no obvious connection between the estate and the Middle East.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The gateway is also adorned with panels bearing the coats of arms of the Lairds of Powis.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The Estate of Powis was owned by the Frasers—their crest is shown on the towers—until the marriage of an heiress to a Leslie.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The house was the home of John Leslie, Professor of Greek at Kings College.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] It was subsequently owned by the Burnett family.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Burnett sold most of the estate to Aberdeen Town Council who built a housing estate in the area comprising over 300 residences.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The Sir Duncan Rice Library was designed by Danish architects Schmidt Hammer Lassen and completed in 2011.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] It was officially opened by Queen Elizabeth II in September 2012 and named after Duncan Rice, a previous Principal of the university.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] This seven-storey tower, clad in zebra-like jagged stripes of white and clear glass, replaced the smaller Queen Mother Library as the university's main library and can be seen prominently from the entire campus and much of the city.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] It is open to the public and outstanding views of the city and coastline are available from the upper floors.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] In addition to expanded facilities it also houses public exhibition space and the university's historic collections, comprising more than a quarter of a million ancient and priceless books and manuscripts collected over five centuries since the university's foundations.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Other libraries are in the Taylor Building on the same campus (for law books and materials) and at Foresterhill (for medicine and medical sciences).
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The university's library service (i.e. including all libraries) holds over one million books.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The most recent building is the Science Teaching Hub.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Completed in 2021, the building contains laboratories for subjects including biological sciences, chemistry, geosciences and medical sciences.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The Aberdeen Sports Village, located across King Street from the Old Aberdeen campus, houses sports facilities and the aquatics centre.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The university's Foresterhill Campus is located approximately 1.75 kilometres (1.09 mi) to the east of the Old Aberdeen campus and is home to the university's Life Sciences and Medicine facilities.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] It is co-located with Aberdeen Royal Infirmary, Royal Aberdeen Children's Hospital and Aberdeen Maternity Hospital, all teaching hospitals operated by regional health board NHS Grampian.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The campus accommodates the School of Medicine, Medical Science and Nutrition; the School of Psychology; and the School of Biological Sciences.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] It also includes the Rowett Institute of Nutrition and Health, the Institute of Medical Sciences, Institute of Applied Health Sciences, Institute of Dentistry, and Institute of Education for Medical & Dental Sciences.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The Foresterhill site is managed jointly with NHS Grampian.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The university has had a presence at Foresterhill since around 1938, and the management of the site was formalised in 1997 by the completion of an operational agreement between the two parties.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] A new campus in Doha, Qatar was established in May 2017.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Known as AFG College with the University of Aberdeen, it is a partnership with Al Faleh Group for Educational and Academic Services (AFG).
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] It offers undergraduate and postgraduate programmes in business, law, linguistics, social science, computing science and public health.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Marischal College is a neo-Gothic building, having been rebuilt in 1836–41, and greatly extended several years later.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Formerly an open three-sided court, the college now forms a quadrangle as additions to the buildings were opened by Edward VII in 1906 and form the current facade from Broad Street.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The building is widely considered to be one of the best examples of neo-Gothic architecture in Great Britain; the architect, Alexander Marshall Mackenzie was a native of Aberdeen as well as an alumnus of the university.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The Mitchell Tower at the rear is named for the benefactor (Dr Charles Mitchell) who paid for the graduation hall.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The opening of this tower in 1895 was part of celebrations of the 400th anniversary of the university.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Until 1996, Marischal College housed the Departments of Molecular & Cell Biology and Biomedical Sciences, which had been there for many decades.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] From 1996, the departments moved to Kings College campus and Foresterhill campus.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Teaching no longer takes place at Marischal College, with many of the departments formerly based there having moved to King's College some decades previously.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] While graduations and other events (e.g. concerts) took place in the cathedral-like Mitchell Hall in the north wing, for many years much of the building (including the frontage to the street) was derelict.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The majority of the building was leased to Aberdeen City Council in 2008, with significant re-development taking place to allow the council to occupy it as its new administrative headquarters.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Occupation of the rear portion of the building is retained by the university including the former Marischal Museum and Mitchell Hall, which was used previously for graduation and other academic ceremonies before moving to Elphinstone Hall at King's College.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] A small campus at Hilton became part of the university estate following a merger in 2001 between the university and the Aberdeen campus of the Northern College of Education, and temporarily became home to the university's Faculty of Education.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] It was less than a mile southwest of King's College campus.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Following the renovation of the MacRobert Building at King's College to house the School of Education (completed in 2005), the Hilton campus was closed and sold to developers.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The campus was demolished and the land is now occupied by a residential development called "The Campus".
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] In common with the other ancient universities in Scotland, the university's structure of governance is largely regulated by the Universities (Scotland) Acts of 1858.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] This gives the university a tripartite constitution comprising the General Council of senior academics and graduates, the University Court responsible for finances and administration, and the Academic Senate (*Senatus Academicus*)—the university's supreme academic body.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] There are correspondingly three main officers of the university.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] It is nominally headed by the chancellor, a largely ceremonial position traditionally held by the Bishop of Aberdeen, but as a result of the Scottish Reformation holders are now elected for life by the General Council.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] There is also a rector of the university, who chairs the University Court and is elected by the students for a three-year term to represent their interests.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] There are also four assessors, ten masters, including the principal and vice principal, and the factor or procurator.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The administrative head and chief executive of the university is its principal and vice-chancellor.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The principal acts as chair of the *Senatus Academicus*, and his status as vice-chancellor enables him to perform the functions reserved to the chancellor in the latter's absence, such as the awarding of degrees.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The university's three most significant officials are its chancellor, principal, and rector, whose rights and responsibilities are largely derived from the Universities (Scotland) Act 1858.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The chancellor is the nominal head of the university.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The chancellor since 2013 is Queen Camilla.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] She is the first female chancellor of the university.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The chancellor, or, if necessary, his or her deputy, confers degrees on graduates and chairs the university's General Council.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The principal and vice-chancellor of the university is Professor Peter Edwards, having succeeded George Boyne in November 2025.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Professor Edwards was previously the university's Vice-Principal for Regional Engagement and has been with the university for over 35 years.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The rector of the university has been—since 1860—elected by the students to serve a three-year term of office; before that, the office was appointed.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The rector's duties are to chair meetings of the University Court and to represent student views on that body.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] In November 2024, Iona Fyfe, a Scottish folk singer, was elected by the student body of the university as the new rector.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Other notable Aberdeen rectors have included Winston Churchill, Andrew Carnegie, H.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Asquith, Maggie Chapman and Clarissa Dickson Wright, who was Aberdeen's first female rector.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] This body was created by the commissioners during the merger of King's and Marischal in 1870.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] It was part of a series of reforms introduced to rectify the method of government, with the Court acting as a court of appeal from the Senatus.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The Court originally consisted of six members; the rector, representing the students, the principal, and one assessor each to the chancellor, the rector, the General Council and the Senatus.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] However, today the Court consists of many more members.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The Court's principal role is to oversee the management of the revenue, property and other resources of the university.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The Academic Senate (Latin: *Senatus Academicus*) is the supreme academic body for the university.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Its members include all the professors of the university, certain senior readers, a number of senior lecturers and lecturers and elected student senate representatives.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] It is responsible for authorising degree programmes and issuing all degrees to graduates, and for managing student discipline.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The president of the Senate is the university principal.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The university is divided into 12 schools which are organised within a broad range of disciplines, with the larger schools sub-divided into three teaching colleges.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Multi-disciplinary institutes and research centres allow the university's experts to collaborate on pioneering research projects.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] In the financial year ending 31 July 2024, Aberdeen had a total income of £264 million (2022/23 – £268.6 million) and total expenditure of £188.9 million (2022/23 – £259.3 million).
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] At year end, Aberdeen had endowments of £65.3 million (2023 – £58.6 million) and total net assets of £431 million (2023 – £352.4 million).
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The university's coat of arms is an integral part of the current logo, which along with the colours burgundy and white, is used extensively on campus signage, printed materials, and online.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The university's coat of arms incorporates those of the founders and locations of the two colleges it is derived from.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] In the top left quadrant are the arms of the burgh of Old Aberdeen, with the addition of a symbol of knowledge being handed down from above.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Top right are those of George Keith, the fifth Earl Marischal.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Bottom left are those of Bishop William Elphinstone.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The bottom right quarter is a simplified version of the three castles which represent the city of Aberdeen (this symbol of the city also appears prominently on the arms of The Robert Gordon University).
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The motto of the University of Aberdeen is *Initium Sapientiae Timor Domini*, which translates from Latin as "*The beginning of wisdom is fear of the Lord*".
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] It is a quote from the Old Testament of the Bible, Psalm 111, verse 10.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] It also appears in the Book of Proverbs (9:10).
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The motto can be seen at the archway beside New King's on the High Street at the King's College campus, as well as other campus locations and in formal settings such as on graduation certificates.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] A university tartan was created in 1992 as part of the celebrations for the 500th anniversary of the university which took place in 1995.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The tartan was designed by the Weavers Incorporation of Aberdeen and Harry Lindley and incorporates colours from the university's coat of arms.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Academic dress has been worn in the University of Aberdeen since mediaeval times.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Aberdeen shared with the other ancient universities the wearing of scarlet gowns (*toga rubra*) and a trencher for undergraduates, but by the middle of the twentieth century its use amongst the students had faded.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Bursars formerly wore a black gown, and were made to perform menial services about college.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Female students wore a trencher with scarlet tassels, while male students wore black tassels.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Academic dress is usually worn only at formal occasions, such as at graduation, Founder's Day, or academic processions which take place for ceremonial reasons.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] MA, BSc, LLB etc.), a long black gown is worn with a hood of black silk and lined with silk in a colour which varies depending on discipline.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] For example, the lining is white silk for all Master of Arts degrees, green silk for Bachelor of Science in pure sciences, and crimson silk for MBChB.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] MSc, MLitt etc.) a long black gown is worn, with a white silk hood lined in a colour that varies by discipline.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] For PhD, the doctor's scarlet robe is worn with black facings and sleeve lining, along with a black "John Knox" cap.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] EdD, LLD etc.), the scarlet robe has facings and sleeve linings in a different colour.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The academic year at Aberdeen was originally based upon the Scottish Term and Quarter Days, beginning with Martinmas (October – November), Candlemas (January – March), and ending with Whitsunday (April – June).
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] However, today the academic term is divided into two semesters, the First Half-Session and the Second-Half Session, beginning in September and ending in May.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Written examinations are sat in November and April and May, and graduation is celebrated either in November or at the end of June.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Aberdeen was ranked 119th in the world in *TIME* magazine's 2026 ranking of the world's top universities.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] In 2025, Aberdeen was consistently ranked among the top 250 universities in the world and consistently ranked within the top 25 universities in the United Kingdom by *The Guardian* and *The Times*.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] In the 2019 *Times Higher Education University Impact Rankings*, Aberdeen was ranked 31st in the world for impact on society.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Over 75 per cent of the university's research was classified as 'world leading' or 'internationally excellent' in the 2014 Research Excellence Framework.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Its highest internationally ranked subject is Divinity and Religious Studies, which is ranked at joint 25th in the world and 7th in the UK.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Economics was ranked 11th in the UK by Times Subject Rankings and 12th in the UK by Complete University Guide 2019.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] In 2022, the university formed an international university alliance with the University of Calgary in Alberta, Canada and Curtin University in Perth, Australia to address global challenges together.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The alliance provides joint research centres, collaborative academic programs, industry linkage, and student and staff mobility exchanges.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The university is a member of the University of the Arctic and participates in its mobility program, north2north, which enables students of member institutions to study in different parts of the North.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] In the 2024/25 academic year, the student body consisted of 13,930 students, composed of 9,815 undergraduates and 4,115 postgraduate students.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The university is designated as a 'medium-tariff' institution by the Department for Education, with the average undergraduate entrant to the university in recent years amassing between 122–130 UCAS Tariff points in their top three pre-university qualifications.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Based on 2022/23 HESA entry standards data published in domestic league tables, which include a broad range of qualifications beyond the top three exam grades, the average student at the University of Aberdeen achieved 184 points – the tenth highest in the United Kingdom.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The university has one of the smallest percentages of students from lower-class backgrounds, being ranked fifth from bottom for class equality.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The university participates in widening access schemes such as the Children's University, REACH Scotland, Access Aberdeen, and ASPIRENorth, in order to promote a more widespread uptake of those traditionally under-represented at university.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The Gifford Lectures, established in 1887 by Adam Gifford, began at the university (along with the other ancient universities in Scotland) with E.B Tylor's lecture on the Natural History of Religion between 1889 and 1891.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] Since then, over 30 Gifford Lectures have been given at the university, with some distinguished figures including Hannah Arendt, Alfred North Whitehead, Karl Barth, Paul Tillich, Michael Polanyi, N.T.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] A public lecture series was held in 2011 to commemorate the 400th anniversary of the publication of the King's James Bible.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The university is also host to the annual Andrew Carnegie Lecture Series which began in 2014, with the first lecture given by Matthew Barzun.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p01] The Elphinstone Institute hosts its own monthly lecture series, which began in 2016, in the MacRobert Building, with lectures usually given on local or Scottish topics.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] The library was first located in the nave of King's College Chapel and then moved to a new site in the college in 1870.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] The current library contains one of the most extensive university library collections in the United Kingdom, with over a million volumes and a quarter of a million ancient and priceless books and manuscripts, including the Hortus sanitatis.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] The library at Aberdeen was given the right of legal deposit under the Statute of Anne (1710) but this was rescinded in 1837, and as a result has a rare collection of pre-Victorian novels.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] The core of the original library at King's College was formed from Elphinstone's books that he left to the university.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] The books were originally housed in a room in the south east tower (now the round tower).
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] They were then moved to a building on the south side of Kings College Chapel, and in 1773 to the west end of the chapel.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] They were located in 1870 to a new building as illustrated.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] This library was extended in 1885, with galleries being installed in 1912, reading desks in 1932 and a mezzanine floor in 1964.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] The Queen Mother Library had been the university's main library since 1965, and the original library in King's College was replaced with the King's College Conference Centre in 1991.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] The Queen Mother Library was refurbished and expanded in 1982.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] The Sir Duncan Rice Library was officially opened on 24 September 2012 by Her Majesty Queen Elizabeth accompanied by the Duke of Edinburgh, replacing the Queen Mother Library.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] It was designed by the Danish architectural firm Schmidt Hammer Lassen at the cost of £57 million.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] The building sits on a base of Scottish stone.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] The ground floor is double-height with seven floors above.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] The building is clad in zebra-like jagged stripes of white and clear glass.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] In the interior void spaces are located centrally.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] Contrasting with the geometric exterior, the central atrium formed by the void spaces has an organic form, shifting in location across the levels.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] It has won numerous awards for its architecture.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] The university also has the Taylor Law Library which is located in the Taylor Building in Old Aberdeen, and the Medical Library on the Foresterhill Campus, which covers the Medicine and Medical Sciences disciplines.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] Christ's College also possesses its own Divinity library.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] The university maintains several museums and galleries, open free to the public.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] The university's collections are internationally renowned and are recognised as of national significance by the Scottish Government.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] Originating in the eighteenth century, they now have over 300,000 items across a wide range of Human Culture, Medicine and Health, and Natural History.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] The Zoology Museum is officially classified as a Recognised Collection of national significance to Scotland and features displays from protozoa to the great whales, including taxidermy, skeletal material, study skins, fluid-preserved specimens and models.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] As of 2024/25 the university had 13,930 students, of which 4,115 were postgraduates.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] In 2009/10 students represented 120 countries with about 46% men, 54% women.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] Of all of undergraduates, 19% were mature students (i.e. aged 25 years or more).
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] The university has more than 550 different undergraduate degree programmes and more than 120 postgraduate taught programmes.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] The student body is represented by a students' association known as Aberdeen University Students' Association (AUSA).
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] Additionally, the elected Rector of the University of Aberdeen serves along with the AUSA president and another sabbatical officer as students' representatives on the University Court.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] AUSA does not operate a traditional students' union, instead operating out of a university building, The Students Union Building, formerly The Hub, helping to support students and provide events and studying space.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] A large students' union formerly occupied a granite building on the corner of Gallowgate and Upperkirkgate in the city centre, opposite Marischal College, but it closed in 2003.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] A second, smaller union opened at nearby Littlejohn Street a couple of years later, but by 2010 it too had closed.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] The organisation has been involved in the creation of "The Hub", a university-owned dining and social centre created by an extensive renovation of the former Central Refectory at the King's College campus.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] It provides facilities for the whole university community (students and staff) and opened in 2006.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] A more traditional social space, the Butchart Student Centre, opened in 2009.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] It acts as the HQ of the Students' Association and provides a wide range of student facilities, but due to city council licensing regulations there is no bar.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] The Butchart Centre includes facilities for student societies and offices.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] The Butchart Centre was converted from what had been the campus sports centre before the opening of the Aberdeen Sports Village nearby.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] AUSA operates out of the Johnston Building.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] "BookEnds" which sells second-hand books with profits going towards charity was initially established in the Butchart Recreation Centre but now operates in the AUSA building.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] There are over a hundred clubs and societies formally affiliated with the students' association.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] The students' association is responsible for sport at the university, which is managed by the Aberdeen University Sports Union, an AUSA committee.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] All registered students are eligible to join any of these clubs or societies.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] The university's oldest student organisation is the Aberdeen University Debater, founded by JF Maclennan in 1848 as the King's College Debating Society.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] In 1871, a Literary Society was started by WM Ramsay, and four years later a Choral Society came to life.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] In 1884, the society also took the first steps towards the introduction of a students' representative council under support from Alexander Bain, the then Rector.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] The creation of the Union in 1895 provided a new debating chamber in Marischal College and the society's first permanent home.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] The chamber beneath Mitchell Hall in Marischal College is Scotland's oldest purpose-built debating chamber.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] In 1998, an alumni fund called the Aberdeen Future Fund was founded, run by the Development Trust.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] It has raised over £2.5 million of unrestricted funds.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] Past projects have included a book fund for the Heavy Demand section in the library, providing "Safe Campus" leaflets, contributing to the student hardship fund, providing training mannequins for Clinical Skills, the organ for King's College Chapel, and funding for intramural sports.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] Established in 1889, it is affiliated to the BUCS and SSS and encompasses over fifty sports clubs.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] There are large playing fields at the back of King's College and also Aberdeen Sports Village, a partnership between the University of Aberdeen, Aberdeen City Council and sportscotland.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] An extension containing the aquatics centre opened on 5 May 2014.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] The Aberdeen University Football Club was formed in 1872, and currently competes in the SJFA North First Division.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] The Aberdeen University Rugby Football Club was founded in 1871, and has a long history of producing both Scottish and British Lions players.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] The annual boat race between Aberdeen University Boat Club and Robert Gordon University Boat Club has been competed for since 1995.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] The University of Aberdeen has lost only four times, in 2006, 2009, 2012 and 2013.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] Aberdeen Sports Village served as one of the official pre-games training venues of the Cameroon Olympic Team prior to the London 2012 Olympic Games.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] There are a large number of ensembles at the University of Aberdeen.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] Some are directed by academic staff, while others are run by students both in and out of the department and include; Balinese Gamelan, Baroque Ensemble, Big Band, Cantores ad Portam, Chapel Choir, Choral Society, Concert Band, String Orchestra and Symphony Orchestra.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] The Aberdeen Student Show is a musical and theatrical show, usually with a strong comedy element, staged every year since 1921.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] Its purpose is to raise money for charity, as part of the Aberdeen Students' Charities Campaign.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] A number of its writers, performers and musicians have gone on to greater renown in the fields of theatre, media and the arts.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] The first successful university newspaper, *Alma Mater*, began under the auspices of the University of Aberdeen Debating Society in 1883.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] The *Alma Mater* was replaced by *The Gaudie*, which has been in circulation since 1934, and is currently free-of-charge.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] *The Gaudie* is recognised as one of the oldest student newspapers in Scotland and the United Kingdom.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] The University of Aberdeen also hosts a chapter of Her Campus, a magazine targeted at female students that publishes yearly magazines showcasing society member's written work.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] Other student media organisations include Granite City TV and Aberdeen Student Radio (ASR).
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] Although these have both become inactive.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] In 2020, the WayWORD Festival was launched by the university's WORD Centre for Creative Writing.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] It has featured notable headliners including Val McDermid, Irvine Welsh and Douglas Stuart.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] Until 2019, each year a student-led torcher parade was held.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] First held in 1889, it was the largest of its kind in Europe.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] Student groups and societies build floats and parade in fancy dress through the city centre to raise money for local charities.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] Traditionally spectators donated money in the form of coppers, a colloquial term for 1p and 2p coins.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] Halls of residence are managed by the university.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] Two large concentrations of university accommodation are provided on the campus in Old Aberdeen and one mile north at the Hillhead Student Village, accessible by a walk through Seaton Park.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] Campus accommodation in the heart of Old Aberdeen consists of self-catered King's Hall and Elphinstone Road Halls.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] The university has a "First-Year Accommodation Guarantee" providing that the student accept their firm offer before a set date prior to the beginning of term.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] In 2014–15, the university ran out of rooms and had to resort to temporary accommodation.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] The university continues to monitor accommodation costs and where possible offers discretionary support to students, to improve access to higher education.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] The first modern halls of residence built by the university on the King's College campus was Crombie halls, named after James Edward Crombie.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] The Crombie-Johnston halls were closed in 2017 following a decline in demand for catered accommodation.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] The Elphinstone Road halls were completed in 1992.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] The Sponsio Academica is the oath, originally in Latin, taken by students matriculating into the four ancient Scottish universities (Edinburgh, St.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] This tradition now has been digitised at Aberdeen and is agreed to as part of an online matriculation process.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] Originally, new students matriculated in Mitchell Hall where the Chancellor would give a welcoming address.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] Usually held annually in February, on Founders' Day, the university community pays tribute to its historic origins as an ancient university and in particular, the role played by William Elphinstone and other benefactors in the establishment of the university.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] The ceremony begins with an academic procession through the university and concludes with a service in King's College Chapel.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] Talks are given by university lecturers and invited guests.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] A candle is lit in the chapel to give thanks to Elphinstone and the other patron fathers.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] The rector, an ancient post dating back to the foundation of the university in 1495, is the students' representative, particularly in welfare matters, and sits on the University Court.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] Tradition dictates that the University of Aberdeen's new rector must ride through Old Aberdeen aloft a bull carried at shoulder height by students of the university.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] The ceremony includes a colourful academic procession representing civic, student and academic life in Aberdeen.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] University staff and students, along with representatives from the City and Aberdeenshire Councils, Incorporated Trades, MSPs, and alumni, attend the ceremony which is followed by a reception in the King's Conference Centre.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] The reception culminates with the new Rector being carried by the student mascot, Angus the Bull, from King's College to the St Machar Bar in the High Street of Old Aberdeen, where tradition also dictates that they buy a round of drinks for their student supporters.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] Bajan, a medieval term (literally 'yellow beak' – bec jaune), describing trainees in the pre-student year, was traditionally applied to the university's first year undergraduates.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] Female undergraduates were referred to as "bajanellas".
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] Second year students were called 'Semis', and these usually played jokes upon or clashed with bajans.
[src:matthew-hay/aberdeen-university-p02] Semis would usually tear first year's gowns.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] Agnosticism contrasts with theism, which affirms God's existence, and atheism, which denies it.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] It is understood either as a neutral middle ground between the two or as a rejection of their shared assumption that knowledge is attainable.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] Agnosticism is often characterized as an informed indecision by someone who has reflected on the issue but has not reached a conclusion, distinguishing agnostics from those who have never considered the issue.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] It is related to skepticism and fallibilism, which deny that knowledge or absolute certainty is possible.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] Various arguments for and against agnosticism are discussed in the academic literature.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] Proponents typically hold that evidence regarding God's existence is inconclusive and that intellectual humility demands suspending judgment.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] Different groups of critics contend that there is decisive evidence either for or against God's existence, or that the absence of decisive evidence leaves disbelief, rather than the suspension of judgment, as the default attitude.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] Agnosticism is often associated with a secular lifestyle that resembles atheism in practice.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] However, it does not necessarily preclude religion.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] For example, agnostic theists believe in God while denying that true knowledge of the divine is possible.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] The term *agnosticism* was coined in the 19th century by Thomas Henry Huxley, who rejected speculative theological and metaphysical conclusions without sufficient evidence.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] However, its precursors and theoretical roots trace back to antiquity, including ideas found in ancient Greek and Indian thought.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] Agnosticism is a stance questioning the existence of God or the divine.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] It is a neutral position in which an individual neither affirms nor denies God's existence.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] Instead, they withhold judgment and remain open to both possibilities.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] Agnosticism is typically contrasted with belief and disbelief, and is understood either as the absence of both or as a distinct attitude, such as a settled indecision.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] A commonly discussed criterion is that the agnostic has considered the question of God's existence but has not reached a positive or negative conclusion.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] In this sense, someone who does not comprehend the question or has never thought about it, such as an infant, does not count as agnostic.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] Agnostics are often motivated by the idea that the available evidence is inconclusive, preferring to withhold assent as an expression of intellectual humility rather than adopt a dogmatic stance.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] Philosophers often define agnosticism in a stronger sense as the theory that the existence of God is unknowable.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] This attitude goes beyond suspension of belief by embracing the claim that human cognition is too limited to access or verify this information.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] In its broadest sense, agnosticism is not restricted to religious questions but can be applied to any field.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] For example, a person can be agnostic about the truth of string theory or the existence of free will if they are unable to reach a verdict on these issues.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] Agnosticism is often contrasted with theism and atheism and treated either as a middle ground between the two or as a rejection of their shared assumption that knowledge about God is attainable.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] Some approaches group agnosticism with atheism as an irreligious attitude in which belief in God is absent.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] However, agnostics are not necessarily opposed to religion and may engage in some religious practices and traditions while remaining uncommitted about God's existence.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] The word *agnosticism* derives from the Ancient Greek terms ἀ- (*a-*), meaning 'not, without', and γνῶσις (*gnōsis*), meaning 'knowledge'.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] It was coined by Thomas Henry Huxley in a speech to the Metaphysical Society in 1869 to describe the view that humans lack the cognitive capacity to attain definitive knowledge about God and related matters.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] Agnosticism is discussed in several fields of inquiry, including theology, philosophy of religion, psychology of religion, religious studies, and the social sciences.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] Various types of agnosticism are discussed in the academic literature, distinguished by the kind of attitude, form of inquiry, and scope of subject matter.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] Psychological or doxastic agnosticism is a suspension of judgment.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] In this sense, a person is agnostic if they have considered God's existence but neither believe nor disbelieve it.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] Psychological agnosticism describes someone's state of mind without implying that this state is rational or demanded by a general lack of evidence.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] It contrasts with epistemological or cognitive agnosticism, which asserts that the existence of God is unknown or unknowable.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] Epistemological agnosticism argues that humans are unable to acquire this kind of information or that there is insufficient evidence to reach a definitive verdict.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] Some versions maintain that no evidence is available, while others hold that the evidence for and against is mixed or balances out.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] In either case, epistemological agnosticism concerns what people should or should not believe, not what they actually believe.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] Accordingly, it rejects both theism and atheism for claiming more than the evidence permits.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] Epistemological agnosticism is sometimes interpreted as skepticism about God because of its focus on the limits of knowledge.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] A related distinction focuses on the degree of commitment.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] Weak agnosticism is a personal attitude of someone who neither believes nor disbelieves.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] It is a lack of conviction in which an individual does not commit to either option without generalizing this stance into a universal claim about what others can or cannot know.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] Strong agnosticism, by contrast, embraces the more assertive position that knowledge of God's existence is impossible.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] The contrast between weak and strong agnosticism is sometimes framed as a claim about what is reasonable to believe.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] In this sense, weak agnosticism holds that it is rational to suspend judgment about God.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] This view does not deem theism and atheism irrational; it merely treats suspension of judgment as a permissible option.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] Strong agnosticism, by contrast, involves the wider claim that agnosticism is the *only* viable option, meaning that claims about the existence or non-existence of God lack sufficient justification and should be withheld.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] A different set of distinctions targets the inquiry involved in the agnostic stance.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] Grounded agnosticism is the result of serious inquiry: the person has considered the options, tried to gather evidence, and reflected on the arguments for and against.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] After taking everything into account, they have concluded that neither belief nor disbelief is decisively justified, leading them to see the matter as unresolvable.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] Ungrounded agnosticism, by contrast, withholds judgment without engaging in substantive investigation.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] In this case, the person understands the issue and has a basic idea of how an inquiry could proceed but has not undertaken it, for example, because they do not consider the issue important enough.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] The term *stored agnosticism* is sometimes used for an even weaker form in which a person lacks an opinion because they have never considered the issue.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] However, it is controversial whether this attitude should be regarded as a genuine form of agnosticism since no deliberate assessment of the issue was involved.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] Another distinction is between optimistic, pessimistic, and hesitant agnosticism, which agree about the current lack of knowledge but disagree about the prospects of future inquiry.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] According to optimistic agnosticism, also called *temporary agnosticism in practice*, the issue may be decided in the future.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] In this case, a person suspends judgment but remains open to the possibility that future discoveries could provide decisive evidence one way or the other.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] Pessimistic agnosticism, or permanent agnosticism in principle, rejects this possibility.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] It holds that the question is irresolvable in principle, meaning that no amount of inquiry can settle the matter.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] Hesitant agnosticism is undecided both about the issue itself and about the prospects of future inquiry.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] Accordingly, it is unsure whether further investigation can provide evidence or whether the obstacles to knowledge are insurmountable.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] Pessimistic forms of agnosticism differ over whether the problem is with available evidence or with the underlying fact.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] According to evidence-based views, the available evidence is insufficient to settle the matter.
[src:matthew-hay/agnosticism] One suggestion holds that there is no serious evidence and that all proposed arguments fall short of the standards of rationality.
